values:
It's funny how different people look at their birthdays, two of my well-meaning co-workers kept trying to let the rest of the staff know that today was my birthday.&nbsp; I think they felt bad because it got lost in the shuffle of the Nurse whose last day was today.&nbsp; I think they thought maybe I was just being overly humble, but I was grateful not to be the center of the attention.&nbsp; However, I am very grateful to those who took the time to wish me &quot;Happy Birthday.&quot;

Things are finally getting less frantic at work.&nbsp; I probably haven't mentioned it, but I work in a Hospital and we've spent the last four months gearing up to move to electronic medical records.&nbsp; Which is very exciting and really fantastic for patient care, but following so close after losing the department's director its put a lot more work on my shoulders so after spending 8-10 hours at work most of the time I just couldn't face more time on the computer which is why I've been absent for so long.

Anyway its late, I just wanted to pop in and say &quot;Hey I'm still alive.&quot;&nbsp;

So I disappeared for the summer without a word to anyone because life kept throwing me curve balls.&nbsp; It started June 1st during our team meeting where I was informed that because one of our locations was closing on weekends and a person was leaving for nursing school that I was not going to be able to increase my hours.&nbsp; This was a huge blow, I've been needing more than 24 hours a week since Mom lost her job because of the stroke, but haven't gotten it so have been robbing Peter to pay Paul and cutting corners where I could just to eek by.&nbsp; The San Francisco Bay Area is a frightfully expensive place to live and I've been under tons of stress just trying to keep a roof over our heads and food on the table.&nbsp; My response to that was to inform my boss and co-workers that I would be looking for a new job and would take the first one offered to me.&nbsp; Since I work every weekend and they'd have to divide those amongst themselves I thought this was the right thing to do.&nbsp; Apparently no one took me seriously.

During the summer I worked 40 hours a week, covering vacations, yet still managed 1-2 interviews a week.&nbsp; The job search was pretty discouraging because each position had 75-100 applicants, but since I was an internal candidate with loads of experience I kept being included as they whittled the pool down to a manageable 10-20 to interview.&nbsp; Not the best odds, but I believe that the Universe places us where we need to be at the right time so we can do what needs to be done.&nbsp; 

Anyway so I am busy doing the job hunting when my brother announces he's gotten in at the last moment into an out of state wilderness EMT program.&nbsp; Basically we had to help him prep for a 6-week course in Colorado with a 1-week camping survival component in just a few days.&nbsp; You might be wondering why he couldn't do it all himself, well that's because he was in the middle of studying for his Chemistry summer school class final at the same time.&nbsp; Then just to complicate the matter my Mom's younger brother announces since he can't get a job in California as a teacher, he's accepted a position in Colorado and needs our help with the move.&nbsp; While my brother needed us just to follow up on his to do list, my uncle needed mom and me to help him a lot more including helping clean his apartment.&nbsp; Let's just say I'm glad I've watched so much &quot;How Clean Is Your House?&quot; on BBC America because it was a horrible mess.&nbsp; It was rough, because we drove two hours north to help, cleaned all day and left at 10pm that night so I could be at work at 5am the next day.

A lot of other stuff happened, none of it terribly interesting so I'll just skip to the more recent stuff.&nbsp; Michael came back a certified W-EMT and is now considering a slight change to his education plans instead of Med school he wants to become a Flight RN.&nbsp; I'm supportive of that because I always worried about his ability to handle a patient's death.&nbsp; My brother's a libra and a sensitive guy, he's the sort that feels things deeply, but is also the strong silent type who doesn't share easily.&nbsp; I remember how hard each death has hit him and had concerns that being responsible for someone's care who died would be devastating.

My uncle in Colorado seems to be alright, though we haven't heard much from him since Mom shared what happened as a result of her posting and answering on yahoo answers.&nbsp; Basically long story short, my Grandma fell in love with a man and married him.&nbsp; It was only later that she discovered from her mother that a) the marriage wasn't valid and b) she wasn't the only wife he had in the area.&nbsp; Apparently my great grandmother didn't give her much choice and threw him out of the house with a verbal thrashing.&nbsp; For the last few years as Mom and I have been trying to learn more about the man, neither of us quite believing the stories and family gossip which made him out to be just slightly less worse than the devil.&nbsp; We've pieced together a different picture of the love story, but wondered what happened to him afterword.&nbsp; So Mom decided to post a message asking for help on yahoo answers last year, but it wasn't until recently that she went back and found someone searching for her as a result of that post.&nbsp; It was a younger half-brother, Bill, who filled in the gaps with e-mails and phone calls.&nbsp; We're going to try and do a reunion soon since Mom now has six siblings she's never met.&nbsp; Anyway, David still believes the negative stories he's grown up with and I think feels Mom has betrayed Grandma so hasn't talked to her since she mentioned Bill and the others.

Mom has good days and bad days, after the last two trips to the ER, one of which resulted in an over night stay it looks like she's had a couple of small strokes called TIA's.&nbsp; Most folks wouldn't notice the changes, but I noticed that her smile is off on one side and she struggles with stuff more than in the past.&nbsp; So the hospital visit did have a good aspect, she met with Occupational and Speech therapists who did some tests and have proof that while Mom is still highly functioning the strokes have caused deficits and altered her thinking.&nbsp; She's going to start rehabilitative therapy and they seemed very postive, but its made us all realize that she'll probably never live on her own again.&nbsp; 

The other day someone asked when I was going to have babies and without thinking I said that I had a baby she was just 50 years old.&nbsp; Its not exactly a fair thing to say because Mom and I watch out for each other, but it shows that at a certain level I've accepted responsibility as her caretaker.&nbsp; I've watched others deal with caretaking, but&nbsp; never realized how much it hurts to realize that your parent isn't there to make everything better anymore.&nbsp; All my life I could depend on my Mom to make everything better, even if it was just talking things out.&nbsp; She's still here and I'm grateful for that, but now its my job to make things better for her.

Which is why I accepted the first job that offered, why I'm balancing two jobs until my transfer goes through on the 26th and why I decided against the two other jobs that were in the process of making an offer.&nbsp; Instead of taking a manager or supervisor position I took an Administrative Assistant job working for a director in the hospital which should be less stress even though it's further up the corporate food chain since my boss reports directly to the head of the hospital and meets frequently with one of the Vice President's.&nbsp; I borrowed my brother's Macy's card and found a great new wardrobe on the clearance racks, but at the same time I've gotten slim enough to wear some of the things I've been carting around for six years.&nbsp; Mom keep teasing me about being a fashinonista because I'm wearing make-up and something more stylish than my birks and jeans, but I know she's proud.&nbsp; 

Between the pills and watching my fat intake I've lost two almost three sizes up top, have gone down from a 46 KK to a 44 II bra and have made some real changes to my lifestyle.&nbsp; Just last week I shocked her by taking a slider roast beef sandwich (4 g fat with mayo and the new hawaiian slider rolls), a salad with fat-free dressing and newton's apple fruit crisp (2.5 g fat which tastes a lot like a low fat version of mcdonald's apple pies).&nbsp; I love veggies but never cared for salad, yet here I was taking it voluntarily.&nbsp; 

In some ways its like I've been doing my own version of Tim Gunn's Guide to Style show, I started by massively overhauling my wardrobe gone is anything that made me look fat, like the baggy t-shirts that hid my shape.&nbsp; They've been replaced by clothes that show I have a waist, legs and breasts.&nbsp; Have ditched my birkenstocks most of the time in favor of ballet flats and Dr. Scholls pumps.&nbsp; I am enjoying my new short haircut and wear bare minerals makeup everyday.&nbsp; I feel like a totally different person than the one who went to that meeting in June.&nbsp; As everything has begun settling down, I've found more time for writing and am really looking forward to NaNoWriMo this year.

So the visit with the Neurologist went fairly well.&nbsp; I now know that what's happening is not in my imagination.&nbsp; One of my co-workers jokingly suggested I was a hypochondriac when the symptoms first started.&nbsp; However it seems serious enough now that the doctor's order another round of blood tests, 2 EEGs (one will test visual &amp; audio input), an MRI, a nerve conduction test and a new medication that I should be able to take while working.&nbsp;&nbsp; There were parts that didn't go so well like some of the reflex tests, I barely felt it when he used the tool to tap different places and when I couldn't feel the vibrating instrument as much as I should have.&nbsp; I'm scared of the MRI test because I'm already kinda claustrophobic and mom got really claustrophobic after hers.&nbsp; I'm also torn for being glad that he marked the epilepsy box as the reason for the MRI and a fear (probably the result of watching too much House) of finding out it is something worse.&nbsp; My Dad had brain tumors when he was young, my cousin had juvenile onset of huntington's, mom had a stroke and my maternal grandmother and both paternal aunts had cancer (2 had breast cancer and 1 had leukemia).

When I got home I did a little research on the tests, epilepsy and my meds hoping that having information would make me feel better, that whole knowledge is power idea.&nbsp; I'm trying not to psych myself out and it worked for a while; I remembered that there are so many more worse illnesses to have like cancer or MS or parkinsen's (the list goes on of course) which aren't as successfully treated with a pill. 

That feeling lasted until I spoke with my Supervisor by phone.&nbsp; When we talked on Friday she made a point that I should communicate with her more and not try to resolve things on my own.&nbsp; Keeping that in mind I decided to give her a heads up&nbsp; to mention that since the side effects of the med causes drowsiness, lack of coordination and dizziness among other things that the med literature seemed to be recommending not to drive and that I was planning to work my shifts remotely from home.&nbsp; 

I was shocked when she basically pointed out that if I couldn't drive then I probably couldn't do my job.&nbsp; My job requires me to use a mouse to select staff who are on the phones, use a drop down menu to chose their new setting and watch what's happening to the incoming calls to our call center.&nbsp; So I guess moving a mouse is exactly like driving a 2700 lb vehicle :-P 

Anyway I was gobsmacked, because that was not the reaction I expected. &nbsp; I thought she might be understanding (maybe sympathetic) or at least content that I was making an effort to communicate with her.&nbsp; Instead she left me feeling like my job was in jeopardy because I'm taking meds which have some serious side effects but might stop the electric shocks and jerks.&nbsp; It was just another stress/ frustration/ hurt I could have done without today.&nbsp; 

She did however manage to make me feel even worse when she proceeded to inform me that her supervisor who initially said that our project should work from home as often as possible, changed his mind and now says we can now only work from home when necessary (like my office being closed) or for emergency coverage.&nbsp; It seems strange to me to invest all that money in equipment for me to only use 2 days a week.&nbsp; But there was no point arguing, so instead I'll drive to work tomorrow using extreme caution (I had problems when I drove Monday) and work from the office because its what they want.&nbsp; She knew I'd agree since I can't risk my job since I'm the sole provider for my family of 3. Mom hasn't found a new job, I'll keep looking with my company for another job and my brother is busy finishing up his med school requirements.

She also said she might be driving here on Thursday to do an on-site inspection of my work station and do a ergo evaluation since she's leaving on the 13th for a 5-week archaeological internship.&nbsp; I'm just not sure if things will be better or worse while she's away while one of my co-worker's and her supervisor are covering her absence.

In the mean time I'm trying to think good thoughts, study for my classes and just have faith that everything happens for a reason.&nbsp;

It's been a while since I've posted because I've been dealing with a bunch of stuff in real life and it reduced the amount of extra time I had.&nbsp; One of the changes I've been dealing with are the on-going health issues.&nbsp; It has been frustrating to say the least because just as my elbow injury seemed to be finally healing and I began working on a new story a new problem crept up.&nbsp; It started one Friday morning as I was driving to work, an intense pain like someone had stuck a cattle prod behind my left knee.&nbsp; Since it only happened once I went on like normal, but over the next couple of days it happened with more frequency.&nbsp; It wasn't just this shooting pain striking various parts of my body that finally had me seek out the weekend clinic it was the addition of a tingling, itchy, creepy crawly feeling like bugs crawling up my skin and the appearance of several veiny bruises where the worst of the shock pain had been.&nbsp; So the doctor arranged a consult appointment with neurology and prescribed a pill, its used for neuropathy and pain, but at first the side effects from it were worse than the symptoms; after it put me to sleep I would wake up feeling like I had the flu, a migraine and had been beaten.&nbsp; During my post clinic follow-up visit to my doctor she told me I was a little anemic and my red blood cells were a little small.&nbsp; She agreed with the clinic doctor that a visit to neurology was a good idea and ordered more detailed blood tests about the anemia. &nbsp; Didn't get the results back yet, but started taking a multi-vitamin which should help if the anemia is caused by iron, B6, B12 or vitamin E deficiency.

Well the neurology consult is today at 9am and I'm really looking forward to it.&nbsp; I had one last year for the ongoing numbness and tingling I was feeling so I know what to expect.&nbsp; He'll push, prod and poke me with pins, but I'd really like a better answer than what I got last year (it will go away on its own).&nbsp; Because yesterday I had the most embarrassing day at work.&nbsp; I'm hoping its because of the medication and not something worse, but long story short I had set down my mug of tea had a muscle jerk and sent it flying into the keyboard and cpu.&nbsp; It was so embarrassing having to call IT and have them come up and deal with the dead keyboard and cpu.&nbsp; What's worse is I debated looking for the lid for the mug that morning but chose not too because I was already running really late for work.&nbsp; Anyway, things seem to be getting better a little bit at a time, so that gives me hope.

The other major change that's been filling up my time and causing loads of stress is that my building is no longer open on weekends, but I still work every weekend.&nbsp; I knew I was going to be guaranteed my regular hours, but oh the stress of not knowing.&nbsp; Anyway the company finally agreed that my department could do a test program with us working from home.&nbsp; So now I've joined the ranks of tele-commuters (just in time as even the cheap local gas is rising to over $4.35 a gallon) and while I do like it the hassle of getting there was rough.&nbsp; I had to make room in my small apartment for another office space because of the equipment they sent home, basically a full computer workstation sans desk and chair.&nbsp; The ergo guy at work is looking into how they can get me a chair.&nbsp; The prep work at home has involved a lot of spring cleaning and clearing clutter including going through boxes still unpacked from the move in 2004.&nbsp; 

Much of the apartment looks like an episode of clean house before they cleaned it up, but others are quite organized, so its a work in progress.&nbsp; One fabulous thing that came out of the decluttering was I went through my closet and tried on all my clothes getting rid of the too big, way too small and unwearable.&nbsp; During that process I discovered I could wear my old interview suit and am back to the size I was 6 years ago.&nbsp; This is fantastic news because it means I have this great Macy's working wardrobe I bought with my yearly bonus all those years ago once I drop a couple more pounds.&nbsp; 

Needless to say I've gotten re-energized about exercising and eating right.&nbsp; Mom's got us on a very low fat diet only about 20g of fat per day.&nbsp; That number is based on Dr. Dean Ornish's book "Reversing Heart Disease" where he's had remarkable results with patients with severe heart disease and blockages.&nbsp; The pictures from the before and after angiograms are amazing.&nbsp; We aren't really doing it for heart disease, but because our doctor told mom to get her cholesterol down to 70 because of the stroke.&nbsp; Ours was pretty good before Mom was 153 and I was 168 so I think its a realistic target.&nbsp; It has been interesting reading labels, which has lead to different choices and some great discoveries.&nbsp;&nbsp; One of the best discoveries is Hebrew National's 98% fat free hot dogs, which my brother loves because they taste just like a full fat beef hot dog, but eating 2 of them is healthier than 1 regular hot dog.&nbsp;&nbsp; To go with that discovery was Bush's Vegetarian baked beans which are fat free.&nbsp; Finally my last two fav discoveries came as I looked for a replacement for soda, I've been soda free for most of the last six months.&nbsp; So in looking through through all the drink sections I found Kern's Horchata in Albertson's fridge section and Numi's in the tea section.&nbsp; Horchata is a Mexican drink  a combo of milk, sugar, water, rice flour and spices.&nbsp; Its a little like egg nog, but really refreshing when paired with tacos, burritos, quesadillas and enchiladas.&nbsp; As a California native I eat lots of Mexican food so the store bought Horchata is a little luxury.&nbsp; My other indulgence is a sorta expensive tea.&nbsp; I've fallen in love with Numi's Decaf Black Vanilla tea and Golden Chai tea, both are worth the extra expense and if you like a hint of exotic Indian cuisine you'll love these too.

So lots of changes, but I'll try to spend more time on the journal in the future; though that may vary since I'm picking up tons of extra shifts for work and taking 2 summer school classes.&nbsp; TTFN

Mom was watching the local news, it gave another reason for the writer's strke to end - Bush needs their help with his speeches apparently the state of the union was like a bad rerun of recent speeches.

So today was the first day of school, I'm a little worried that I've gotten myself in over my head.&nbsp; (Not a big surprise, I seem to do that every time.)&nbsp; While I was eating dinner I finally got a glimpse into how the next chapter of WEL could start.&nbsp; I wrote it down, but had to focus on school for the time so I'll try and get some time in the morning.&nbsp; The one bad thing about my classes is the Wednesday night chat, I'm hoping it doesn't conflict with the chat/writing times Jen already set up; after having such a great first outing I hope to keep it up.&nbsp; 

Last night I watched Billie Piper in "Mansfield Park" and whoever wrote that screenplay needs to be taped to a chair, gagged and forced to listen to someone read Jane Austen's book over and over again.&nbsp; I suppose if I'd never read the book or watched any of the other versions I might have enjoyed it, but given my knowledge I hated it.&nbsp; In the end Mom and I agreed to finish watching it just to see the outcome.&nbsp; It was like watching an accident scene, the inconsistencies, the cultural errors and the like.&nbsp; So I was really disappointed because the Persuasion adaptation while not strictly adhering to the book was at least enjoyable.

The one great piece of news today is Mom and I drove downtown to take my brother to lunch between classes.&nbsp; I drove us there, but when it came time to find a parking space Mom suggested that I pull over and let her drive.&nbsp; Which I did of course since this is the first time since the stroke where she's wanted too.&nbsp; It went well though only lasted like 10 minutes, but still its more progress.&nbsp; 

At lunch we went to Quiznos a place I've only been to once before so I got a little adventurous and ordered the flat bread chopped salad with roasted chicken and honey-dijon vinegrette.&nbsp; It was okay, except the bacon was like under cooked and cold, so I picked it out,&nbsp; but other than that pretty good though the portion was big enough so I could have it for dinner as well.&nbsp; That fairly healthy decision was followed by shopping where I managed to adhere to mom's new dietary restrictions (doctor wants her cholesterol under 100) while resisting temptation.&nbsp;&nbsp; At this point I've managed to cut out all soda, reduce my sugar, fat and salt intake.&nbsp; When I went to the Doctor twice in one week a few weeks ago I had lost&nbsp; like three pounds between Monday and Friday.&nbsp; Which takes my weight loss since August up to like 45 pounds, still a long way to go, but with exercise and these dietary changes it should grow.&nbsp; Part of Mom's tactics to keep me on the band wagon includes watching "You Are What You Eat" on BBC America each day.&nbsp; Seeing the gross way they show folks eating and present the food pretty well grosses me out and keeps me on track.
